This paper proposes a new model for sentence meaning and processing that combines word embeddings with formal semantics and event knowledge. The model is evaluated on compositionality datasets, which are commonly used in computational linguistics and natural language processing research. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which focuses on the intersection of computer science and linguistics. The paper also uses machine learning techniques to train and evaluate the model, which suggests that it could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper uses graph-based representations of event knowledge, which could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
